FIELD	O
OF	O
THE	O
INVENTION	O
The	O
present	O
invention	O
relates	O
generally	O
to	O
speech	O
processing	O
and	O
to	O
large	O
vocabulary	O
continuous	O
speech	O
recognition	O
(	O
LVCSR	O
)	O
systems	O
.	O
More	O
particularly	O
,	O
the	O
present	O
invention	O
relates	O
to	O
a	O
search	O
method	O
based	O
on	O
single	O
triphone	O
tree	O
for	O
large	O
vocabulary	O
continuous	O
speech	O
recognizer	O
.	O

BACKGROUND	O
OF	O
THE	O
INVENTION	O
A	O
speech	O
recognition	O
system	O
recognizes	O
a	O
collection	O
of	O
spoken	O
words	O
(	O
“	O
speech	O
”	O
)	O
into	O
recognized	O
phrases	O
or	O
sentences	O
.	O
A	O
spoken	O
word	O
typically	O
includes	O
one	O
or	O
more	O
phones	O
or	O
phonemes	O
,	O
which	O
are	O
distinct	O
sounds	O
of	O
a	O
spoken	O
word	O
.	O
Thus	O
,	O
to	O
recognize	O
speech	O
,	O
a	O
speech	O
recognition	O
system	O
must	O
not	O
only	O
employ	O
the	O
acoustic	O
nature	O
of	O
the	O
speech	O
,	O
but	O
must	O
also	O
utilize	O
the	O
relationships	O
between	O
the	O
words	O
in	O
the	O
speech	O
.	O
A	O
common	O
way	O
of	O
representing	O
the	O
acoustic	O
nature	O
of	O
the	O
speech	O
is	O
by	O
using	O
an	O
acoustical	O
model	O
such	O
as	O
a	O
hidden	O
markov	O
model	O
(	O
HMM	O
)	O
.	O
A	O
common	O
way	O
of	O
representing	O
the	O
relationships	O
between	O
words	O
in	O
recognizing	O
speech	O
is	O
by	O
using	O
a	O
language	O
model	O
.	O

Typically	O
,	O
a	O
HMM	O
uses	O
a	O
series	O
of	O
transitions	O
from	O
state	O
to	O
state	O
to	O
model	O
a	O
letter	O
,	O
a	O
word	O
,	O
or	O
a	O
sentence	O
.	O
Each	O
state	O
can	O
be	O
referred	O
to	O
a	O
phone	O
or	O
a	O
triphone	O
(	O
phone	O
having	O
a	O
left	O
and	O
right	O
context	O
)	O
.	O
Each	O
arc	O
of	O
the	O
transitions	O
has	O
an	O
associated	O
probability	O
,	O
which	O
gives	O
the	O
probability	O
of	O
the	O
transition	O
from	O
one	O
state	O
to	O
the	O
next	O
at	O
an	O
end	O
of	O
an	O
observation	O
frame	O
.	O
As	O
such	O
,	O
an	O
unknown	O
speech	O
signal	O
can	O
be	O
represented	O
by	O
ordered	O
states	O
with	O
a	O
given	O
probability	O
.	O
Moreover	O
,	O
words	O
in	O
an	O
unknown	O
speech	O
signal	O
can	O
be	O
recognized	O
by	O
using	O
the	O
ordered	O
states	O
of	O
the	O
HMM	O
.	O

To	O
improve	O
speech	O
recognition	O
accuracy	O
,	O
language	O
models	O
can	O
be	O
used	O
in	O
conjunction	O
with	O
an	O
acoustical	O
model	O
such	O
as	O
the	O
HMM	O
.	O
A	O
language	O
model	O
specifies	O
the	O
probability	O
of	O
speaking	O
different	O
word	O
sequences	O
.	O
Examples	O
of	O
language	O
models	O
are	O
N-gram	O
probabilistic	O
grammars	O
,	O
formal	O
grammars	O
,	O
and	O
N-grams	O
of	O
word	O
classes	O
.	O
Typically	O
,	O
the	O
models	O
are	O
represented	O
as	O
a	O
phonetic	O
tree	O
structure	O
wherein	O
all	O
of	O
the	O
words	O
that	O
are	O
likely	O
to	O
be	O
encountered	O
reside	O
at	O
the	O
ends	O
of	O
branches	O
or	O
at	O
nodes	O
in	O
the	O
tree	O
.	O
Each	O
branch	O
represents	O
a	O
phoneme	O
.	O
All	O
the	O
words	O
that	O
share	O
the	O
same	O
first	O
phoneme	O
share	O
the	O
same	O
first	O
branch	O
,	O
and	O
all	O
words	O
that	O
share	O
the	O
same	O
first	O
and	O
second	O
phonemes	O
share	O
the	O
same	O
first	O
and	O
second	O
branches	O
,	O
and	O
so	O
on	O
.	O

A	O
common	O
type	O
of	O
phonetic	O
tree	O
is	O
a	O
triphone	O
tree	O
.	O
A	O
triphone	O
is	O
a	O
phoneme	O
having	O
a	O
left	O
phoneme	O
context	O
and	O
right	O
phoneme	O
context	O
.	O
Thus	O
,	O
a	O
triphone	O
assumes	O
that	O
the	O
way	O
a	O
phoneme	O
is	O
pronounced	O
depends	O
on	O
its	O
neighboring	O
phoneme	O
contexts	O
.	O
To	O
recognize	O
large	O
continuous	O
speech	O
,	O
a	O
first	O
word	O
can	O
be	O
recognized	O
using	O
a	O
triphone	O
tree	O
.	O
Typically	O
,	O
to	O
recognize	O
a	O
second	O
word	O
while	O
maintaining	O
a	O
relationship	O
with	O
the	O
first	O
word	O
,	O
the	O
triphone	O
tree	O
related	O
to	O
the	O
first	O
word	O
must	O
be	O
copied	O
.	O
Hence	O
,	O
a	O
disadvantage	O
of	O
the	O
triphone	O
tree	O
copying	O
technique	O
is	O
the	O
redundant	O
copying	O
of	O
triphone	O
trees	O
to	O
recognize	O
words	O
thereby	O
causing	O
speech	O
recognition	O
process	O
to	O
be	O
slow	O
and	O
large	O
amounts	O
of	O
memory	O
to	O
be	O
consumed	O
.	O

Another	O
technique	O
uses	O
a	O
single	O
triphone	O
tree	O
fast	O
match	O
algorithm	O
to	O
avoid	O
copying	O
of	O
triphone	O
trees	O
.	O
This	O
technique	O
is	O
typically	O
used	O
as	O
a	O
forward	O
pass	O
of	O
a	O
forward/backward	O
recognition	O
process	O
.	O
That	O
is	O
,	O
a	O
second	O
pass	O
must	O
be	O
employed	O
for	O
obtaining	O
higher	O
speech	O
recognition	O
accuracy	O
.	O
In	O
particular	O
,	O
the	O
first	O
pass	O
serves	O
only	O
as	O
a	O
fast	O
match	O
operation	O
and	O
its	O
purpose	O
is	O
to	O
keep	O
the	O
likely	O
word	O
endings	O
in	O
guiding	O
the	O
second	O
pass	O
.	O
Thus	O
,	O
a	O
disadvantage	O
of	O
this	O
technique	O
is	O
that	O
it	O
must	O
be	O
followed	O
by	O
an	O
additional	O
second	O
pass	O
beam	O
search	O
process	O
that	O
requires	O
additional	O
processing	O
time	O
and	O
resource	O
use	O
.	O

